# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: statistics-fundamentals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is named after Thomas Bayes, a minister, statistician, and philosopher.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes used conditional probability to provide an algorithm (his Proposition 9) that uses evidence to calculate limits on an unknown parameter.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] His work was published in 1763 as *An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes studied how to compute a distribution for the probability parameter of a binomial distribution (in modern terminology).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] After Bayes's death, his family gave his papers to a friend, the minister, philosopher, and mathematician Richard Price.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Price significantly edited the unpublished manuscript for two years before sending it to a friend who read it aloud at the Royal Society on 23 December 1763.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Price edited Bayes's major work "An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances" (1763), which appeared in *Philosophical Transactions*, and contains Bayes' theorem.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Price wrote an introduction to the paper that provides some of the philosophical basis of Bayesian statistics and chose one of the two solutions Bayes offered.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In 1765, Price was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in recognition of his work on Bayes's legacy.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] On 27 April, a letter sent to his friend Benjamin Franklin was read out at the Royal Society, and later published, in which Price applies this work to population and computing 'life-annuities'.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Independently of Bayes, Pierre-Simon Laplace used conditional probability to formulate the relation of an updated posterior probability from a prior probability, given evidence.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] He reproduced and extended Bayes's results in 1774, apparently unaware of Bayes's work, and summarized his results in *Théorie analytique des probabilités* (1812).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The Bayesian interpretation of probability was developed mainly by Laplace.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] About 200 years later, Sir Harold Jeffreys put Bayes's algorithm and Laplace's formulation on an axiomatic basis, writing in a 1973 book that Bayes' theorem "is to the theory of probability what the Pythagorean theorem is to geometry".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Stephen Stigler used a Bayesian argument to conclude that Bayes' theorem was discovered by Nicholas Saunderson, a blind English mathematician, some time before Bayes, but that is disputed.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Thomas Bruss reviewed Bayes's "An essay towards solving a problem in the doctrine of chances" as communicated by Price.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] He agreed with Stigler's analysis on many points, but not on the question of priority.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bruss underlined the intuitive part of Bayes's formula and added independent arguments about Bayes's probable motivation for his work.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] He concluded that, unless the contrary is proven, the name "Bayes' Theorem" or "Bayes' formula" is justifiable.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The "Bayes factor" or "likelihood" that appears when writing Bayes' theorem in odds form appears in the early 1940s work of Alan Turing, who called it the "factor in favour of a proposition".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In 1878, Charles Sanders Peirce used the logarithm of this factor as the "weight of evidence" for a proposition.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] where A and B are events and $P(B)\neq 0$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem may be derived from the relation between joint and conditional probabilities.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The events A and not- A , written $\neg A$ , are a mutually exclusive and exhaustive pair.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Suppose that a doctor is testing a patient for the presence of a certain disease.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The patient either has the disease or does not; the test returns either positive or negative.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Let E be the event that the patient has the disease. $P(E)$ is the probability that the patient has the disease.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Let F be the event that the patient tests positive.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The probability that the patient has the disease given that they test positive is thus denoted $P(E|F)$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] For example, if all patients with pancreatic cancer have certain symptoms, it does not follow that anyone who has those symptoms has pancreatic cancer.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Assuming the incidence rate of pancreatic cancer is 1/100000, while 10/99999 healthy people have the symptoms, the probability that a person who has the symptoms has pancreatic cancer is 9.1%.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Based on incidence rate, the following table presents the corresponding numbers per 100,000 people.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Suppose a particular test for whether someone has been using a drug (e.g., Substance D) is 99% sensitive, meaning the true positive rate (TPR) = 0.99.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The test then has 99% true positive results (correct identification of drug use) for drug users.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The test is also 99% specific, meaning its true negative rate (TNR) = 0.99.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Therefore, the test correctly identifies 99% of non-use for non-users, but also generates 1% false positives, or false positive rate (FPR) = 0.01, for non-users.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] An urn contains coins of three different types: A, B, and C.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Coins of type A are fair and, when flipped, come up heads with probability 0.5.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Coins of type B are biased and have probability 0.6 of turning up heads, and type-C coins come up heads with probability 0.9.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The urn contains 2 type-A coins, 2 type-B coins and 1 type-C coin.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] A coin is drawn at random from the urn and flipped.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem gives the probability of a coin being of a given type given that it comes up heads: $P(A|H)={\frac {P(H|A)P(A)}{P(H)}},$ and likewise for $P(B|H)$ and $P(C|H)$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The denominator can be found via the law of total probability: $P(H)=P(H|A)P(A)+P(H|B)P(B)+P(H|C)P(C).$ Assuming the coins are drawn from the urn at random, $P(A)=2/5$ , $P(B)=2/5$ , and $P(C)=1/5$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The interpretation of Bayes' rule depends on the interpretation of probability ascribed to the terms.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The two predominant classes of interpretation are described below.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In Bayesian (or epistemological) interpretations, probability measures a rational "degree of belief".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem links the degree of belief in a proposition before and after rationally accounting for evidence.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] For example, in a medical testing scenario, if a patient tests positive for a disease, the doctor will find it more plausible that the patient has that disease.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] For more on the application of Bayes' theorem under Bayesian interpretations of probability, see Bayesian inference.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In the frequentist interpretations, probability measures a "proportion of outcomes".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] For example, suppose an experiment is performed many times.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] *P*(*A*) is the proportion of outcomes with property *A* (the prior) and *P*(*B*) is the proportion with property *B*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] *P*(*B*|*A*) is the proportion of outcomes with property *B* *out of* outcomes with property *A*, and *P*(*A*|*B*) is the proportion of those with *A* *out of* those with *B* (the posterior).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In many applications, for instance in Bayesian inference, the event *B* is fixed in the discussion and we wish to consider the effect of its having been observed on our belief in various possible events *A*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In such situations the denominator of the last expression, the probability of the given evidence *B*, is fixed; what we want to vary is *A*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In other words, the posterior is proportional to the prior times the likelihood.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] This holds for values x and y within the support of *X* and *Y*, ensuring $f_{X}(x)>0$ and $f_{Y}(y)>0$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Let $P_{Y}^{x}$ be the conditional distribution of Y given $X=x$ and let $P_{X}$ be the distribution of X .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Existence and uniqueness of the needed conditional expectation is a consequence of the Radon–Nikodym theorem.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Andrey Kolmogorov formulated this in 1933.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] He underlined the importance of conditional probability, writing, "I wish to call attention to ... the theory of conditional probabilities and conditional expectations".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem determines the posterior distribution from the prior distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Uniqueness requires continuity assumptions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem can be generalized to include improper prior distributions such as the uniform distribution on the real line.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Modern Markov chain Monte Carlo methods have boosted the importance of Bayes' theorem, including in cases with improper priors.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Probabilities are sometimes specified in terms of odds.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] For any proposition A , the ratio of the probability that A is true to the probability that A is false is called the odds on A .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem can be written using odds as follows.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In symbols: $O(A|B)=O(A){\frac {P(B|A)}{P(B|\neg A)}}.$ This is often summarized by saying that the *posterior odds* are the *prior odds* times the likelihood.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] For example, suppose that a disease has a prevalence of 1%, i.e., the probability that a randomly chosen person is infected is 0.01.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] And suppose that a test for the disease returns the correct result with 99% probability.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The desired result is obtained by identifying both expressions and solving for $P(A\vert B\cap C)$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In subjective interpretations of probability theory, an event's probability is regarded as an agent's belief that the event will happen.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is widely invoked to justify how an agent should update or modify their beliefs after receiving new information.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] If an agent assigns the probability $P(A)$ to the event A , $P(B)$ to the event B , and $P(B|A)$ to the event " B happens assuming A has already happened", Bayes' theorem gives the value of $P(A|B)$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Suppose that, after the agent has made these probability assignments, event B occurs.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] An agent who follows *Bayesian updating,* also known as updating by *conditionalization,* will change their probability for event A from the old value $P(A)$ to the new value $P'(A)=P(A|B)$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Conditionalization is not the only updating rule that might be considered rational.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The issue of which assumptions can be invoked to constrain updating rules remains somewhat controversial.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In quantum mechanics, probability distributions are generalized to density matrices, arrays of complex numbers that describe the preparation of a quantum system.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] A *quantum Bayes rule* can be formulated that expresses how density matrices are updated as new experimental data about a system is obtained.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In Bayesian statistics, an object or system is represented by a mathematical model that contains one or more numerical parameters.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] The available information about the system is used to write a probability distribution over the possible values of those parameters, indicating which values are more plausible than others.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is then used to update that probability distribution as new evidence is obtained.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' rule and computing conditional probabilities provide a method to solve a number of popular puzzles, such as the Three Prisoners problem, the Monty Hall problem, the Boy or Girl paradox, and the two envelopes problem.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Alan Turing and his collaborators at Bletchley Park pioneered the use of Bayes' theorem for breaking ciphers during World War II.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In 1941, Turing wrote a set of pedagogical notes introducing Bayesian methods of cryptanalysis by applying them to problems like solving a Vigenère cipher, which were simpler than his team's primary focus, reading messages encrypted by the Enigma machine.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem was also applied to the cracking of the Japanese naval code JN 25.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] In genetics, Bayes' rule can be used to estimate the probability that someone has a specific genotype.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Many people seek to assess their chances of being affected by a genetic disease or their likelihood of being a carrier for a recessive gene of interest.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] A Bayesian analysis can be done based on family history or genetic testing to predict whether someone will develop a disease or pass one on to their children.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is employed in evolutionary biology to deduce trees of relationships among species that best explain the available data.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/bayes-theorem] This approach was made practical by the use of Markov chain Monte Carlo methods.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] In probability theory, the **central limit theorem** (**CLT**) states that, under appropriate conditions, the distribution of a normalized version of the sample mean converges to a standard normal distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] This holds even if the original variables themselves are not normally distributed.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] There are several versions of the CLT, each applying in the context of different conditions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The theorem is a key concept in probability theory because it implies that probabilistic and statistical methods that work for normal distributions can be applicable to many problems involving other types of distributions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] This theorem has seen many changes during the formal development of probability theory.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Previous versions of the theorem date back to 1811, but in its modern form it was only precisely stated in the 1920s.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] In other words, suppose that a large sample of observations is obtained, each observation being randomly produced in a way that does not depend on the values of the other observations, and the average (arithmetic mean) of the observed values is computed.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] If this procedure is performed many times, resulting in a collection of observed averages, the central limit theorem says that if the sample size is large enough, the probability distribution of these averages will closely approximate a normal distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The central limit theorem has several variants.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] In its common form, the random variables must be independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] This requirement can be weakened; convergence of the mean to the normal distribution also occurs for non-identical distributions or for non-independent observations if they comply with certain conditions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The earliest version of this theorem, that the normal distribution may be used as an approximation to the binomial distribution, is the de Moivre–Laplace theorem.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The classical central limit theorem describes the size and the distributional form of the stochastic fluctuations around the deterministic number μ {\displaystyle \mu } ({\displaystyle \mu }) during this convergence.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] where sup {\displaystyle \sup } ({\displaystyle \sup }) denotes the supremum (i.e. least upper bound) of the set.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] In this variant of the central limit theorem the random variables X i {\textstyle X_{i}} ({\textstyle X_{i}}) have to be independent, but not necessarily identically distributed.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] In practice it is usually easiest to check Lyapunov's condition for δ = 1 {\textstyle \delta =1} ({\textstyle \delta =1}).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] If a sequence of random variables satisfies Lyapunov's condition, then it also satisfies Lindeberg's condition.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The converse implication, however, does not hold.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] In the same setting and with the same notation as above, the Lyapunov condition can be replaced with the following weaker one (from Lindeberg in 1920).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] converges towards the standard normal distribution N ( 0 , 1 ) {\textstyle {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)} ({\textstyle {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)}).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] For example, the following theorem is Corollary 4 of Robbins (1948).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] It assumes that N {\displaystyle N} ({\displaystyle N}) is asymptotically normal (Robbins also developed other conditions that lead to the same result).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] where → d {\displaystyle \xrightarrow {\,d\,} } ({\displaystyle \xrightarrow {\,d\,} }) denotes convergence in distribution and N ( 0 , 1 ) {\displaystyle {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)} ({\displaystyle {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)}) is the normal distribution with mean 0, variance 1.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The multidimensional central limit theorem states that when scaled, sums converge to a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Summation of these vectors is done component-wise.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The multivariate central limit theorem can be proved using the Cramér–Wold theorem.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] It is unknown whether the factor d 1 / 4 {\textstyle d^{1/4}} ({\textstyle d^{1/4}}) is necessary.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The generalized central limit theorem (GCLT) was an effort of multiple mathematicians (Sergei Bernstein, Jarl Waldemar Lindeberg, Paul Lévy, William Feller, Andrey Kolmogorov, and others) over the period from 1920 to 1937.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The first published complete proof of the GCLT was in 1937 by Paul Lévy in French.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] An English language version of the complete proof of the GCLT is available in the translation of Boris Vladimirovich Gnedenko and Kolmogorov's 1954 book.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] In other words, if sums of independent, identically distributed random variables converge in distribution to some Z, then Z must be a stable distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] A useful generalization of a sequence of independent, identically distributed random variables is a mixing random process in discrete time; "mixing" means, roughly, that random variables temporally far apart from one another are nearly independent.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Several kinds of mixing are used in ergodic theory and probability theory.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] See especially strong mixing (also called α-mixing) defined by α ( n ) → 0 {\textstyle \alpha (n)\to 0} ({\textstyle \alpha (n)\to 0}) where α ( n ) {\textstyle \alpha (n)} ({\textstyle \alpha (n)}) is so-called strong mixing coefficient.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Existence of such δ > 0 {\textstyle \delta >0} ({\textstyle \delta >0}) ensures the conclusion.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] For encyclopedic treatment of limit theorems under mixing conditions see (Bradley 2007).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The central limit theorem has a proof using characteristic functions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] It is similar to the proof of the (weak) law of large numbers.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] where the last step relies on the fact that all of the Y i {\textstyle Y_{i}} ({\textstyle Y_{i}}) are identically distributed.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] where o ( t 2 / n ) {\textstyle o(t^{2}/n)} ({\textstyle o(t^{2}/n)}) is "little o notation" for some function of t {\textstyle t} ({\textstyle t}) that goes to zero more rapidly than t 2 / n {\textstyle t^{2}/n} ({\textstyle t^{2}/n}).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] All of the higher order terms vanish in the limit n → ∞ {\textstyle n\to \infty } ({\textstyle n\to \infty }).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] converges to the normal distribution N ( 0 , 1 ) {\textstyle {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)} ({\textstyle {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)}), from which the central limit theorem follows.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The central limit theorem gives only an asymptotic distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] As an approximation for a finite number of observations, it provides a reasonable approximation only when close to the peak of the normal distribution; it requires a very large number of observations to stretch into the tails.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The convergence in the central limit theorem is uniform because the limiting cumulative distribution function is continuous.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Stein's method can be used not only to prove the central limit theorem, but also to provide bounds on the rates of convergence for selected metrics.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The convergence to the normal distribution is monotonic, in the sense that the entropy of Z n {\textstyle Z_{n}} ({\textstyle Z_{n}}) increases monotonically to that of the normal distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The central limit theorem applies in particular to sums of independent and identically distributed discrete random variables.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The binomial distribution article details such an application of the central limit theorem in the simple case of a discrete variable taking only two possible values.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Studies have shown that the central limit theorem is subject to several common but serious misconceptions, some of which appear in widely used textbooks.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The law of large numbers as well as the central limit theorem are partial solutions to a general problem: "What is the limiting behavior of Sn as n approaches infinity?" In mathematical analysis, asymptotic series are one of the most popular tools employed to approach such questions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Dividing both parts by *φ*1(*n*) and taking the limit will produce *a*1, the coefficient of the highest-order term in the expansion, which represents the rate at which *f*(*n*) changes in its leading term.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Here one can say that the difference between the function and its approximation grows approximately as *a*2*φ*2(*n*).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The idea is that dividing the function by appropriate normalizing functions, and looking at the limiting behavior of the result, can tell us much about the limiting behavior of the original function itself.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Informally, something along these lines happens when the sum, Sn, of independent identically distributed random variables, *X*1, ..., *Xn*, is studied in classical probability theory.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] If each Xi has finite mean μ, then by the law of large numbers, ⁠*Sn*/*n*⁠ → *μ*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Distributions Ξ which can arise in this way are called *stable*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Clearly, the normal distribution is stable, but there are also other stable distributions, such as the Cauchy distribution, for which the mean or variance are not defined.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The scaling factor bn may be proportional to nc, for any *c* ≥ ⁠1/2⁠; it may also be multiplied by a slowly varying function of n.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The law of the iterated logarithm specifies what is happening "in between" the law of large numbers and the central limit theorem.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Specifically it says that the normalizing function √*n* log log *n*, intermediate in size between n of the law of large numbers and √*n* of the central limit theorem, provides a non-trivial limiting behavior.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The density of the sum of two or more independent variables is the convolution of their densities (if these densities exist).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Thus the central limit theorem can be interpreted as a statement about the properties of density functions under convolution: the convolution of a number of density functions tends to the normal density as the number of density functions increases without bound.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] These theorems require stronger hypotheses than the forms of the central limit theorem given above.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Theorems of this type are often called local limit theorems.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] See Petrov for a particular local limit theorem for sums of independent and identically distributed random variables.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Specifically, an appropriate scaling factor needs to be applied to the argument of the characteristic function.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] An equivalent statement can be made about Fourier transforms, since the characteristic function is essentially a Fourier transform.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Let Sn be the sum of n random variables.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Many central limit theorems provide conditions such that Sn/√Var(Sn) converges in distribution to *N*(0,1) (the normal distribution with mean 0, variance 1) as n → ∞.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] In some cases, it is possible to find a constant *σ*2 and function f(n) such that Sn/(σ√n⋅f(n)) converges in distribution to *N*(0,1) as n→ ∞.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] The logarithm of a product is simply the sum of the logarithms of the factors.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Therefore, when the logarithm of a product of random variables that take only positive values approaches a normal distribution, the product itself approaches a log-normal distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Many physical quantities (especially mass or length, which are a matter of scale and cannot be negative) are the products of different random factors, so they follow a log-normal distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] This multiplicative version of the central limit theorem is sometimes called Gibrat's law.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p01] Whereas the central limit theorem for sums of random variables requires the condition of finite variance, the corresponding theorem for products requires the corresponding condition that the density function be square-integrable.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Asymptotic normality, that is, convergence to the normal distribution after appropriate shift and rescaling, is a phenomenon much more general than the classical framework treated above, namely, sums of independent random variables (or vectors).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] New frameworks are revealed from time to time; no single unifying framework is available for now.
