[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] These two εn-close distributions have densities (in fact, log-concave densities), thus, the total variance distance between them is the integral of the absolute value of the difference between the densities.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Convergence in total variation is stronger than weak convergence.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] An important example of a log-concave density is a function constant inside a given convex body and vanishing outside; it corresponds to the uniform distribution on the convex body, which explains the term "central limit theorem for convex bodies".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] In general, however, they are dependent.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] The condition *f*(*x*1, ..., *xn*) = *f*(|*x*1|, ..., |*xn*|) ensures that *X*1, ..., *Xn* are of zero mean and uncorrelated; still, they need not be independent, nor even pairwise independent.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] By the way, pairwise independence cannot replace independence in the classical central limit theorem.
