[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] ), which is called the standard deviation of the mean (since it refers to the spread of sample means).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Regression analysis, and in particular ordinary least squares, specifies that a dependent variable depends according to some function upon one or more independent variables, with an additive error term.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Various types of statistical inference on the regression assume that the error term is normally distributed.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] This assumption can be justified by assuming that the error term is actually the sum of many independent error terms; even if the individual error terms are not normally distributed, by the central limit theorem their sum can be well approximated by a normal distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Given its importance to statistics, a number of papers and computer packages are available that demonstrate the convergence involved in the central limit theorem.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] The actual term "central limit theorem" (in German: "zentraler Grenzwertsatz") was first used by George Pólya in 1920 in the title of a paper.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Pólya referred to the theorem as "central" due to its importance in probability theory.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] According to Le Cam, the French school of probability interprets the word *central* in the sense that "it describes the behaviour of the centre of the distribution as opposed to its tails".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] The abstract of the paper *On the central limit theorem of calculus of probability and the problem of moments* by Pólya in 1920 translates as follows.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] A thorough account of the theorem's history, detailing Laplace's foundational work, as well as Cauchy's, Bessel's and Poisson's contributions, is provided by Hald.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Two historical accounts, one covering the development from Laplace to Cauchy, the second the contributions by von Mises, Pólya, Lindeberg, Lévy, and Cramér during the 1920s, are given by Hans Fischer.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Bernstein presents a historical discussion focusing on the work of Pafnuty Chebyshev and his students Andrey Markov and Aleksandr Lyapunov that led to the first proofs of the CLT in a general setting.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] A curious footnote to the history of the Central Limit Theorem is that a proof of a result similar to the 1922 Lindeberg CLT was the subject of Alan Turing's 1934 Fellowship Dissertation for King's College at the University of Cambridge.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Only after submitting the work did Turing learn it had already been proved.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem-p02] Consequently, Turing's dissertation was not published.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] In statistics, the CLT can be stated as: let $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{n}$ denote a statistical sample of size n from a population with expected value (average) $\mu$ and finite positive variance $\sigma ^{2}$ , and let ${\bar {X}}_{n}$ denote the sample mean (which is itself a random variable).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] Then the limit as $n\to \infty$ of the distribution of $({\bar {X}}_{n}-\mu ){\sqrt {n}}$ is a normal distribution with mean 0 and variance $\sigma ^{2}$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] The classical central limit theorem describes the size and the distributional form of the stochastic fluctuations around the deterministic number $\mu$ during this convergence.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] where $\sup$ denotes the supremum (i.e. least upper bound) of the set.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] In this variant of the central limit theorem the random variables ${\textstyle X_{i}}$ have to be independent, but not necessarily identically distributed.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] The theorem also requires that random variables ${\textstyle \left|X_{i}\right|}$ have moments of some order ${\textstyle (2+\delta )}$ , and that the rate of growth of these moments is limited by the Lyapunov condition given below.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] In practice it is usually easiest to check Lyapunov's condition for ${\textstyle \delta =1}$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {1} _{\{\ldots \}}}$ is the indicator function.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] converges towards the standard normal distribution ${\textstyle {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)}$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] Rather than summing an integer number n of random variables and taking $n\to \infty$ , the sum can be of a random number N of random variables, with conditions on N .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] It assumes that N is asymptotically normal (Robbins also developed other conditions that lead to the same result).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] where $\xrightarrow {\,d\,}$ denotes convergence in distribution and ${\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ is the normal distribution with mean 0, variance 1.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] It is unknown whether the factor ${\textstyle d^{1/4}}$ is necessary.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] See especially strong mixing (also called α-mixing) defined by ${\textstyle \alpha (n)\to 0}$ where ${\textstyle \alpha (n)}$ is so-called strong mixing coefficient.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] exists, and if ${\textstyle \sigma \neq 0}$ then ${\textstyle {\frac {S_{n}}{\sigma {\sqrt {n}}}}}$ converges in distribution to ${\textstyle {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)}$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] The assumption ${\textstyle \sigma \neq 0}$ cannot be omitted, since the asymptotic normality fails for ${\textstyle X_{n}=Y_{n}-Y_{n-1}}$ where ${\textstyle Y_{n}}$ are another stationary sequence.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] Existence of such ${\textstyle \delta >0}$ ensures the conclusion.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] Assume ${\textstyle \{X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n},\ldots \}}$ are independent and identically distributed random variables, each with mean ${\textstyle \mu }$ and finite variance ${\textstyle \sigma ^{2}}$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/central-limit-theorem] The sum ${\textstyle X_{1}+\cdots +X_{n}}$ has mean ${\textstyle n\mu }$ and variance ${\textstyle n\sigma ^{2}}$ .
