[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p01] This is known as the *68–95–99.7 rule*, or *the empirical rule*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p01] The standard deviation matrix S {\displaystyle \mathbf {S} } ({\displaystyle \mathbf {S} }) is the extension of the standard deviation to multiple dimensions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p01] It is the symmetric square root of the covariance matrix Σ {\displaystyle \mathbf {\Sigma } } ({\displaystyle \mathbf {\Sigma } }).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p01] S {\displaystyle \mathbf {S} } ({\displaystyle \mathbf {S} }) linearly scales a random vector in multiple dimensions in the same way that σ {\displaystyle \sigma } ({\displaystyle \sigma }) does in one dimension.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p01] A scalar random variable x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) with variance σ 2 {\displaystyle \sigma ^{2}} ({\displaystyle \sigma ^{2}}) can be written as x = σ z {\displaystyle x=\sigma z} ({\displaystyle x=\sigma z}), where z {\displaystyle z} ({\displaystyle z}) has unit variance.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p01] This requires that S S ′ = Σ {\displaystyle \mathbf {S} \mathbf {S'} =\mathbf {\Sigma } } ({\displaystyle \mathbf {S} \mathbf {S'} =\mathbf {\Sigma } }).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p01] There are then infinite solutions for S {\displaystyle \mathbf {S} } ({\displaystyle \mathbf {S} }), and consequently there are multiple ways to whiten the distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p01] The symmetric square root of Σ {\displaystyle \mathbf {\Sigma } } ({\displaystyle \mathbf {\Sigma } }) is one of the solutions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] The mean and the standard deviation of a set of data are descriptive statistics usually reported together.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] In a certain sense, the standard deviation is a "natural" measure of statistical dispersion if the center of the data is measured about the mean.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] This is because the standard deviation from the mean is smaller than from any other point.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] Variability can also be measured by the coefficient of variation, which is the ratio of the standard deviation to the mean.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] Often, we want some information about the precision of the mean we obtained.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] We can obtain this by determining the standard deviation of the sampled mean.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] where N is the number of observations in the sample used to estimate the mean.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] In order to estimate the standard deviation of the mean *σ*mean it is necessary to know the standard deviation of the entire population σ beforehand.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] However, in most applications this parameter is unknown.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] For example, if a series of 10 measurements of a previously unknown quantity is performed in a laboratory, it is possible to calculate the resulting sample mean and sample standard deviation, but it is impossible to calculate the standard deviation of the mean.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] However, one can estimate the standard deviation of the entire population from the sample, and thus obtain an estimate for the standard error of the mean.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] The following two formulas can represent a running (repeatedly updated) standard deviation.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] Where N, as mentioned above, is the size of the set of values (or can also be regarded as *s*0).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] In a computer implementation, as the two *s**j* sums become large, we need to consider round-off error, arithmetic overflow, and arithmetic underflow.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] The method below calculates the running sums method with reduced rounding errors.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] This is a "one pass" algorithm for calculating variance of n samples without the need to store prior data during the calculation.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] Applying this method to a time series will result in successive values of standard deviation corresponding to n data points as n grows larger with each new sample, rather than a constant-width sliding window calculation.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] And the standard deviation equations remain unchanged.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] *s*0 is now the sum of the weights and not the number of samples N.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] The incremental method with reduced rounding errors can also be applied, with some additional complexity.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] where n is the total number of elements, and n′ is the number of elements with non-zero weights.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] The above formulas become equal to the simpler formulas given above if weights are taken as equal to one.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] The term *standard deviation* was first used in writing by Karl Pearson in 1894, following his use of it in lectures.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] This was as a replacement for earlier alternative names for the same idea: for example, Gauss used *mean error*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] The standard deviation index (SDI) is used in external quality assessments, particularly for medical laboratories.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation-p02] Standard deviation is algebraically simpler, though in practice less robust, than the average absolute deviation.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] The Pareto distribution with parameter $\alpha \in (1,2]$ has a mean, but not a standard deviation (loosely speaking, the standard deviation is infinite).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] We obtain more information and the difference between ${\frac {1}{N}}$ and ${\frac {1}{N-1}}$ becomes smaller.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] where $q_{p}$ is the p-th quantile of the chi-square distribution with k degrees of freedom, and 1 − *α* is the confidence level.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] where $\textstyle \operatorname {var} \,=\,\sigma ^{2}$ and $\textstyle \operatorname {cov}$ stand for variance and covariance, respectively.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] where $\textstyle \operatorname {erf}$ is the error function.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] The standard deviation matrix $\mathbf {S}$ is the extension of the standard deviation to multiple dimensions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] It is the symmetric square root of the covariance matrix $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] $\mathbf {S}$ linearly scales a random vector in multiple dimensions in the same way that $\sigma$ does in one dimension.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] A scalar random variable x with variance $\sigma ^{2}$ can be written as $x=\sigma z$ , where z has unit variance.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] In the same way, a random vector ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ in several dimensions with covariance $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ can be written as ${\boldsymbol {x}}=\mathbf {S} {\boldsymbol {z}}$ , where ${\boldsymbol {z}}$ is a normalized variable with identity covariance $\mathbf {1}$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] This requires that $\mathbf {S} \mathbf {S'} =\mathbf {\Sigma }$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] There are then infinite solutions for $\mathbf {S}$ , and consequently there are multiple ways to whiten the distribution.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] The symmetric square root of $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ is one of the solutions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/standard-deviation] For example, a multivariate normal vector ${\boldsymbol {x}}\sim N({\boldsymbol {\mu }},\mathbf {\Sigma } )$ can be defined as ${\boldsymbol {x}}=\mathbf {S} {\boldsymbol {z}}+{\boldsymbol {\mu }}$ , where ${\boldsymbol {z}}\sim N({\boldsymbol {0}},\mathbf {1} )$ is the multivariate standard normal.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] A **statistical hypothesis test** is a method of statistical inference used to decide whether the data provide sufficient evidence to reject a particular hypothesis.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] A statistical hypothesis test typically involves a calculation of a test statistic.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Then a decision is made, either by comparing the test statistic to a critical value or equivalently by evaluating a *p*-value computed from the test statistic.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Roughly 100 specialized statistical tests are in use.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The goal of a hypothesis test is to establish whether certain properties of a statistical population are true by examining sample data.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Typically, the population is modelled by a random variable whose distribution has unknown parameters.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] For example, a medical trial may wish to establish whether a particular drug is effective in treating high blood pressure, with "the change in blood pressure observed in a patient who takes the drug" being the random variable.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] An example hypothesis could be "the mean change in blood pressure is zero" or "the mean change in blood pressure is negative".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In general, any statement about the parameters describing a **population** can be a hypothesis (but not a statement about the sample).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The test compares two hypotheses: a default "null" hypothesis (denoted H0) and its negation, the "alternative" hypothesis (H1).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Typically the test will select a null hypothesis that the intervention being studied has no effect, or that the population parameter takes some "obvious" value.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] A test statistic is computed from the given sample data, and the tester calculates the conditional probability of observing a value at least this extreme, supposing the null hypothesis is true.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] If this probability (called the p-value) is less than the significance level of the test (denoted $\alpha$ ), then the null hypothesis is rejected.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The test does **not** conclude that the null hypothesis is false, or that the probability that the null hypothesis is false is less than $\alpha$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Because it is usually impossible to definitely establish whether the hypothesis being tested is true or false from a sample, the conclusion of a hypothesis test is not certain to be correct.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] A statistical hypothesis test compares a test statistic (*z* or *t* for examples) to a threshold.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The test statistic (the formula found in the table below) is based on optimality.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] For a fixed level of Type I error rate, use of these statistics minimizes Type II error rates (equivalent to maximizing power).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] While hypothesis testing was popularized early in the 20th century, early forms were used in the 1700s.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The first use is credited to John Arbuthnot (1710), followed by Pierre-Simon Laplace (1770s), in analyzing the human sex ratio at birth; see § Human sex ratio.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Ronald Fisher began his life in statistics as a Bayesian (Zabell 1992), but Fisher soon grew disenchanted with the subjectivity involved (namely use of the principle of indifference when determining prior probabilities), and sought to provide a more "objective" approach to inductive inference.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher emphasized rigorous experimental design and methods to extract a result from few samples assuming Gaussian distributions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman (who teamed with the younger Pearson) emphasized mathematical rigor and methods to obtain more results from many samples and a wider range of distributions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Modern hypothesis testing is an inconsistent hybrid of the Fisher vs Neyman/Pearson formulation, methods and terminology developed in the early 20th century.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher popularized the "significance test".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] He required a null-hypothesis (corresponding to a population frequency distribution) and a sample.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] His (now familiar) calculations determined whether to reject the null-hypothesis or not.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Significance testing did not utilize an alternative hypothesis so there was no concept of a Type II error (false negative).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The *p*-value was devised as an informal, but objective, index meant to help a researcher determine (based on other knowledge) whether to modify future experiments or strengthen one's faith in the null hypothesis.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing (and Type I/II errors) was devised by Neyman and Pearson as a more objective alternative to Fisher's *p*-value, also meant to determine researcher behaviour, but without requiring any inductive inference by the researcher.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman & Pearson considered a different problem to Fisher (which they called "hypothesis testing").
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] They initially considered two simple hypotheses (both with frequency distributions).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] They calculated two probabilities and typically selected the hypothesis associated with the higher probability (the hypothesis more likely to have generated the sample).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Their method always selected a hypothesis.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] It also allowed the calculation of both types of error probabilities.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher and Neyman/Pearson clashed bitterly.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman/Pearson considered their formulation to be an improved generalization of significance testing (the defining paper was abstract; Mathematicians have generalized and refined the theory for decades).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher thought that it was not applicable to scientific research because often, during the course of the experiment, it is discovered that the initial assumptions about the null hypothesis are questionable due to unexpected sources of error.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] He believed that the use of rigid reject/accept decisions based on models formulated before data is collected was incompatible with this common scenario faced by scientists and attempts to apply this method to scientific research would lead to mass confusion.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The dispute between Fisher and Neyman–Pearson was waged on philosophical grounds, characterized by a philosopher as a dispute over the proper role of models in statistical inference.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman accepted a position in the University of California, Berkeley in 1938, breaking his partnership with Pearson and separating the disputants (who had previously occupied the same building).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The dispute between Fisher and Neyman terminated (unresolved after 27 years) with Fisher's death in 1962.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Some of Neyman's later publications reported *p*-values and significance levels.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The modern version of hypothesis testing is generally called the **null hypothesis significance testing (NHST)** and is a hybrid of the Fisher approach with the Neyman-Pearson approach.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Nickerson wrote an article stating that NHST was (at the time) "arguably the most widely used method of analysis of data collected in psychological experiments and has been so for about 70 years" and that it was at the same time "very controversial".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] This fusion resulted from confusion by writers of statistical textbooks (as predicted by Fisher) beginning in the 1940s (but signal detection, for example, still uses the Neyman/Pearson formulation).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Great conceptual differences and many caveats in addition to those mentioned above were ignored.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman and Pearson provided the stronger terminology, the more rigorous mathematics and the more consistent philosophy, but the subject taught today in introductory statistics has more similarities with Fisher's method than theirs.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Sometime around 1940, authors of statistical text books began combining the two approaches by using the *p*-value in place of the test statistic (or data) to test against the Neyman–Pearson "significance level".
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Paul Meehl has argued that the epistemological importance of the choice of null hypothesis has gone largely unacknowledged.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] When the null hypothesis is predicted by theory, a more precise experiment will be a more severe test of the underlying theory.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] When the null hypothesis defaults to "no difference" or "no effect", a more precise experiment is a less severe test of the theory that motivated performing the experiment.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher and Neyman opposed the subjectivity of probability.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Their views contributed to the objective definitions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The core of their historical disagreement was philosophical.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Many of the philosophical criticisms of hypothesis testing are discussed by statisticians in other contexts, particularly correlation does not imply causation and the design of experiments.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing is of continuing interest to philosophers.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistics is increasingly being taught in schools with hypothesis testing being one of the elements taught.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Many conclusions reported in the popular press (political opinion polls to medical studies) are based on statistics.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] An introductory college statistics class places much emphasis on hypothesis testing – perhaps half of the course.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Such fields as literature and divinity now include findings based on statistical analysis (see the Bible Analyzer).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] An introductory statistics class teaches hypothesis testing as a cookbook process.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing is also taught at the postgraduate level.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statisticians learn how to create good statistical test procedures (like *z*, Student's *t*, *F* and chi-squared).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistical hypothesis testing is considered a mature area within statistics, but a limited amount of development continues.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] An academic study states that the cookbook method of teaching introductory statistics leaves no time for history, philosophy or controversy.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing has been taught as received unified method.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Surveys showed that graduates of the class were filled with philosophical misconceptions (on all aspects of statistical inference) that persisted among instructors.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] While the problem was addressed more than a decade ago, and calls for educational reform continue, students still graduate from statistics classes holding fundamental misconceptions about hypothesis testing.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Ideas for improving the teaching of hypothesis testing include encouraging students to search for statistical errors in published papers, teaching the history of statistics and emphasizing the controversy in a generally dry subject.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Select a relevant statistical test with associated test statistic *T*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Derive the distribution of the test statistic under the null hypothesis from the assumptions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In standard cases this will be a well-known result.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] For example, the test statistic might follow a Student's t distribution with known degrees of freedom, or a normal distribution with known mean and variance.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Select a significance level (*α*), the maximum acceptable false positive rate.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Compute from the observations the observed value *t*obs of the test statistic *T*.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Decide to either reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative or not reject it.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The Neyman-Pearson decision rule is to reject the null hypothesis *H*0 if the observed value *t*obs is in the critical region, and not to reject the null hypothesis otherwise.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The former report is adequate, the latter gives a more detailed explanation of the data and the reason why the suitcase is being checked.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Not rejecting the null hypothesis does not mean the null hypothesis is "accepted" per se (though Neyman and Pearson used that word in their original writings; see the Interpretation section).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The processes described here are perfectly adequate for computation.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] They seriously neglect the design of experiments considerations.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] It is particularly critical that appropriate sample sizes be estimated before conducting the experiment.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The phrase "test of significance" was coined by statistician Ronald Fisher.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] When the null hypothesis is true and statistical assumptions are met, the probability that the p-value will be less than or equal to the significance level $\alpha$ is at most $\alpha$ .
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] This ensures that the hypothesis test maintains its specified false positive rate (provided that statistical assumptions are met).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The *p*-value is the probability that a test statistic which is at least as extreme as the one obtained would occur under the null hypothesis.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] At a significance level of 0.05, a fair coin would be expected to (incorrectly) reject the null hypothesis (that it is fair) in 1 out of 20 tests on average.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The *p*-value does not provide the probability that either the null hypothesis or its opposite is correct (a common source of confusion).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] If the *p*-value is less than the chosen significance threshold (equivalently, if the observed test statistic is in the critical region), then we say the null hypothesis is rejected at the chosen level of significance.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] If the *p*-value is *not* less than the chosen significance threshold (equivalently, if the observed test statistic is outside the critical region), then the null hypothesis is not rejected at the chosen level of significance.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the "lady tasting tea" example (below), Fisher required the lady to properly categorize all of the cups of tea to justify the conclusion that the result was unlikely to result from chance.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] His test revealed that if the lady was effectively guessing at random (the null hypothesis), there was a 1.4% chance that the observed results (perfectly ordered tea) would occur.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistics are helpful in analyzing most collections of data.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] This is equally true of hypothesis testing which can justify conclusions even when no scientific theory exists.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the Lady tasting tea example, it was "obvious" that no difference existed between (milk poured into tea) and (tea poured into milk).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistical hypothesis testing plays an important role in the whole of statistics and in statistical inference.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Significance testing has been the favored statistical tool in some experimental social sciences (over 90% of articles in the *Journal of Applied Psychology* during the early 1990s).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Other fields have favored the estimation of parameters (e.g. effect size).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Significance testing is used as a substitute for the traditional comparison of predicted value and experimental result at the core of the scientific method.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] When theory is only capable of predicting the sign of a relationship, a directional (one-sided) hypothesis test can be configured so that only a statistically significant result supports theory.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] This form of theory appraisal is the most heavily criticized application of hypothesis testing.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] "If the government required statistical procedures to carry warning labels like those on drugs, most inference methods would have long labels indeed." This caution applies to hypothesis tests and alternatives to them.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The successful hypothesis test is associated with a probability and a type-I error rate.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The conclusion of the test is only as solid as the sample upon which it is based.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The design of the experiment is critical.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] A statistical analysis of misleading data produces misleading conclusions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The issue of data quality can be more subtle.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In forecasting for example, there is no agreement on a measure of forecast accuracy.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the absence of a consensus measurement, no decision based on measurements will be without controversy.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Publication bias: Statistically nonsignificant results may be less likely to be published, which can bias the literature.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Multiple testing: When multiple true null hypothesis tests are conducted at once without adjustment, the overall probability of Type I error is higher than the nominal alpha level.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Those making critical decisions based on the results of a hypothesis test are prudent to look at the details rather than the conclusion alone.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the physical sciences most results are fully accepted only when independently confirmed.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Bootstrap-based resampling methods can be used for null hypothesis testing.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] A bootstrap creates numerous simulated samples by randomly resampling (with replacement) the original, combined sample data, assuming the null hypothesis is correct.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The bootstrap is very versatile as it is distribution-free and it does not rely on restrictive parametric assumptions, but rather on empirical approximate methods with asymptotic guarantees.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Traditional parametric hypothesis tests are more computationally efficient but make stronger structural assumptions.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In situations where computing the probability of the test statistic under the null hypothesis is hard or impossible (due to perhaps inconvenience or lack of knowledge of the underlying distribution), the bootstrap offers a viable method for statistical inference.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The earliest use of statistical hypothesis testing is generally credited to the question of whether male and female births are equally likely (null hypothesis), which was addressed in the 1700s by John Arbuthnot (1710), and later by Pierre-Simon Laplace (1770s).
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Arbuthnot examined birth records in London for each of the 82 years from 1629 to 1710, and applied the sign test, a simple non-parametric test.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] In every year, the number of males born in London exceeded the number of females.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Considering more male or more female births as equally likely, the probability of the observed outcome is 0.582, or about 1 in 4,836,000,000,000,000,000,000,000; in modern terms, this is the *p*-value.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] Laplace considered the statistics of almost half a million births.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] The statistics showed an excess of boys compared to girls.
[src:statistics-fundamentals/statistical-hypothesis-test] He concluded by calculation of a *p*-value that the excess was a real, but unexplained, effect.
